@node "Background" "What`s Reversi?           "
@{b}WHERE IT CAME FROM..@{ub}

Reversi was first published in 1880 in England.  The game is also known as Othello.  Here in Germany it's published by the famous company Ravensburger.

@{b}THE RULES@{ub}

The board size is 8x8 squares.  The game is played with 2-coloured stones, normally black on one side, white on the other.  Before the first move, the squares D5 and E4 are occupied by the stones of the first player; the second player's stones are on D4 and E5.  In this game, player 1 always starts; however, you can, of course, choose who player 1 is.
Now, the players by turn place a stone in a free square.  If two of, say, the white player's stones are placed at each end of the opponent's row (which may be horizontal, vertical or diagonal), all the black stones between them are turned over, and thus, from that moment on, belong to the white player (this works the other way 'round, too:).  At least one row of stones has to be turned over if possible.  If you can't move for some reason - bad luck.
The aim of the game is (you guess it) to have the most stones on the board in the end.  This happens when
  - all squares are occupied.
  - it's not possible to turn one or more of the opponent's stones.
  - only stones of one colour are left.

If you want to tease me, send a disk with a saved game after you defeated the computer.  But forget it, you won't be able to do it. :)

As far as I know, there are three @{"variations" link "Rows_per_Move" 0} of the game, in which, on any given turn:

1) You can only turn one row per move, even if there are more possibilities.
2) You can turn as many rows as you like ­ of course, at least one.
3) All possible rows have to be turned.

MUIReversi 1.1 knows all of these.

The @{"size" link "Board_Size" 0} of the board can be adjusted between 4x4 and 16x16.  The bigger the board is, the more time the computer needs to think.  The @{"starting position" link "Game_Start" 0} of the four stones can be either diagonal or parallel.
@endnode

@node "Author" "About The Author             "
@{b}ABOUT THE AUTHOR@{ub}

I`m a student of computer sciences at the Universität Stuttgart.  In 1989, I got my first Amiga, which I've been programming with C since then.  I like playing strategy games (e.g. Populous, Civilization or The Settlers).  Because I also like board games, I developed a Reversi for the Amiga a few years ago.  The computer opponent wasn't that intelligent, but it was really comfortable and had a nice interface.
When I saw the @{"Magic User Interface" link "MUI"} system 2 years ago, I thought about what I could do with it and remembered my old Reversi.  So I started to rewrite it, although @{"MUI" link "MUI"} isn't intended for games.  Anyway, I wanted to see what is possible.  After nearly a year, MUIReversi was born ­ it's using @{"MUI" link "MUI"} the whole way.  Luckily, I attended a lecture about programming trees in games at the university, and thus, I had a good base for the computer player, which now plays a lot better than in the old version.

Thanks a lot to my little brother @{b}Heiko@{ub}, who created all the nice pictures.  I like them very much; they give the game a personal touch.  

