@node "Rows_per_Move" "Rows Per Move"
@{b}ROWS PER MOVE@{ub}

Depending on where you place your stone, you may have the possibility to turn more than one row in that move.  MUIReversi lets you choose between three different rules for that case.  

@{fg highlight}turn one row per move:@{fg text} The player can only turn one row per move.  Toggle one of the @{"arrow buttons" link "Direction_Buttons"} to indicate the direction the desired row runs.  

@{fg highlight}turn any rows per move:@{fg text} You can turn as many rows as you like; however, you must turn at least one.  Defining which rows you want to turn works in much the same way as above; however, now you can toggle as many buttons as you want.  

@{fg highlight}turn all rows per move:@{fg text} Since you have no choice but to turn all possible rows, you cannot use the arrow buttons here.  They'll just show you which rows will be turned automatically.  

Choose the rule by clicking on one of the buttons in the @{"variants window" link "Game Variant" 0}.  This window is opened via the @{"Configuration" link "Configuration" 0} menu.  

You'll have to start a new game, so you can only leave this window with the @{" New Game " link "Config_EndButtons" 0} button.  
@endnode

@node "Board_Size" "Board Size"
@{b}BOARD SIZE@{ub}

The original board consists of 8x8 squares.  
...but why shouldn't we try other sizes as well?  That's why you can adjust the size between 4x4 and 16x16 squares.  Notice that the board itself is always a square.  That's why there's only one button to change it in the variants window.  This window is opened via the @{"Configuration" link "Configuration" 0} menu.

You'll have to start a new game, so you can only leave this window with the @{" New Game " link "Config_EndButtons" 0} button.
@endnode

@node "Game_Start" "Start Position"
@{b}START POSITION@{ub}

In the original game, the stones are placed diagonally in the center of the board.
MUIReversi lets you also place the stones parallel.  You can choose between these variants in the @{"variants window" link "Game Variant" 0}.  This window is opened via the @{"Configuration" link "Configuration" 0} menu.

You'll have to start a new game, so you can only leave this window with the @{" New Game " link "Config_EndButtons" 0} button.
@endnode

@node "Config_EndButtons" "The Buttons In The Configuration Window"
@{b}THE BUTTONS IN THE CONFIGURATION WINDOW@{ub}

There are three ways to leave the configuration window:

@{fg highlight}OK:@{fg text} The new configuration is saved in ENV: and ENVARC:.  In some case, e.g. after changing the board size, you'll have to start a new game, and thus, this button might be deactivated.  

@{fg highlight}New Game:@{fg text} The new configuration is saved and a new game is started.  

@{fg highlight}Cancel:@{fg text} Forget any changes made in the configuration.  
@endnode

