@node "PossibleMoves" "Possible Moves"
@{b}THE ITEM POSSIBLE MOVES@{ub}

For all those who don't know the game, it might be handy to let MUIReversi display the possible moves.  You can enable or disable this with this item.  If enabled, all turnable rows are displayed with a small arrow.  Looks nice, try it!  
@endnode

@node "Protocol" "Protocol"
@{b}THE ITEM PROTOCOL@{ub}

The protocol is written in a separate window.  The table contains two rows per line:  yours, and your opponent's.  Only the starting position of the stone is displayed, and turned rows are not shown.  Sorry for that!  

The squares are named like in a chess game:  The upper left corner is A1, and the lower right would be D4, on a 4x4 board.  

This window is not only an information source; you can also 'undo' your moves (cheating is the correct word:) by clicking on one of the lines, or you can move backward and forward in a game.  The selected line becomes white, and the stones' postions are shown on the board.  
Remember, if you jump back in a game and restart from that position, all recorded moves after that move are removed.  Move on....  

See also: button @{"take back move" link "Take_Back_Move" 0} in the main window!  
@endnode

@node "CurrentPlayer" "current player"
@{b}THE CURRENT PLAYER@{ub}

A frame of stones shows the colour of the player whose turn it is.  In this frame, a picture of the player or the computer is displayed.  

If your system doesn't know about datatypes (included in AmigaOS 3.0), you won't see any pictures; however, this won't limit the game in any way.  
@endnode

@node "Player_Status" "Player's Status"
@{b}PLAYER`S STATUS@{ub}

This small box has several functions:
If it's a human player's turn, it displays the appropriate information.  
If it's the computer's turn, it displays the status of the machines' mindwork.  You can interrupt this by clicking in the display.  Another click restarts his thinking.  
@endnode

@node "Take_Back_Move" "Take Back A Move"
@{b}TAKE BACK A MOVE@{ub}

There are two buttons in the main window that let you move forward (right) and backward (left) in the game.
This way, you can undo a move or just look at what's happened in the past moves.

See also: @{"protocol window" link "Protocol" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Direction_Buttons" "Arrow Buttons"
@{b}THE ARROW BUTTONS@{ub}

You choose the row(s) you want to turn by pressing one or more of the arrow buttons.  They point in the same directions as the rows that originate from the stone you placed on the board in this move.

@{fg shine}turn one row per move:@{fg text} You can toggle only one button.  If another one is already pressed, it will be released automatically.

@{fg shine}turn any rows per move:@{fg text} You can toggle all buttons independently on and off.

@{fg shine}turn all rows per move:@{fg text} All buttons are disabled.  They just display the direction(s) of the row(s) that will be turned automatically.

If the cat has stolen your mouse, you can also use the keys 1 through 9 (except 5) on the numeric pad of your keyboard.

@endnode

@node "Execute" "Execute"
@{b}THE EXECUTE BUTTON@{ub}

Since you can select which rows you want to turn, a move cannot be executed automatically.  That's why there's an Execute button.

You can also use the RETURN key of your keyboard ­ or even faster, double click on the board on one of the @{"arrow buttons" link "Direction_Buttons"}.  

@endnode

@node "Game_Board" "Board"
@{b}THE BOARD@{ub}

The board is located in the right half of the main window; you won't miss it.
Each row and column is labeled, which gives each square a unique name.  You'll know that from other board games.  

You select the square in which you want to put your stone with the mouse.  A small black arrow will then point to it.  

After you've placed your stone, you can ­ depending on the selected rule ­ select which rows have to be turned with the @{"arrow buttons" link "Direction_Buttons" 0}.  The rows that are about to be turned are marked with a hatching in the user's colour.  

To execute the move, you'll have to press the @{"Execute button" link "Execute" 0}, or double click on the starting square, or one of the @{"arrow buttons" link "Direction_Buttons" 0}.  

The stones will automatically adjust their size, depending on the size of the board.  
@endnode

@node "Commodity-Interface" "Commodity Interface"
@{b}THE COMMODITY INTERFACE@{ub}

As with any other MUI application, you can enable a commodity interface for MUIReversi.  
The supported functions are:

@{fg shine}show:@{fg text} If MUIReversi is iconified, all windows will reopen.  

@{fg shine}hide:@{fg text} All windows are closed, and an icon will appear on the workbench.  The program is now iconified and its windows can be reopened by double clicking on the icon, or using the 'show' button in Exchange.  

@{fg shine}remove:@{fg text} MUIReversi exits.  

The functions active/inactive are not supported.  
@endnode

@node "AREXX Port" "ARexx-Port"
@{b}THE AREXX-PORT@{ub}

As with any other MUI application, an ARexx port can be activated for MUIReversi.  
The port is labeled Reversi.n (e.g. Reversi.1, Reversi.2 etc.).  Since there's not much use for an ARexx port in this game, it only supports the standard MUI commands.  See your @{"MUI documentation" link "mui:docs/English/MUI.guide/main" 0} for more info on this.  
@endnode

@node "Internal_Multitasking" "Internal Multitasking"
@{b}THE INTERNAL MULTITASKING@{ub}

Although the Amiga is a multitasking machine from the first day on, it's still not usual to use more than one task in an application.  
For MUIReversi, I thought it would be nice if you could still talk to the game while the computer is thinking about the next move.  Therefore, the computer opponents always have their own task.  

Benefits:

  - the window refresh (eg after resizing one of the windows) works any time
  - you can use the computer for both players
  - you can look at the protocol anytime
  - changing the configuration is possible any time

Let the computer play against the computer and iconify the program.  The computer will continue playing!
@endnode

